-- Sensitive Index Breaches 20,000 as India's Economy Lures Foreign Investors
-- B y   R a j h k u m a r   K   S h a a w
-- 2010-09-21T11:28:59Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-21/sensex-index-fluctuates-as-some-investors-judge-recent-advance-as-overdone.html
India’s stocks rose, with the
benchmark index surpassing a key level for the first time in
more than 2 1/2 years, as the economy’s expansion lures funds.  Bharat Heavy Electricals Ltd. , the nation’s biggest power-
equipment maker, advanced for the first day in five after
winning a 26.7 billion rupees ($585 million) order from Visa
Power Ltd. to set up a 1,200 megawatt thermal power plant.
 Larsen & Toubro Ltd. , the nation’s biggest engineering company,
climbed 2 percent. Global investors have poured an unprecedented
$25 billion this year into the nation’s stocks and bonds,
exchange data show.  “Global investors are willing to pay the premium for the
India growth story,” said  Anand Shah , who manages $328 million
as head of equities at Canara Robeco Asset Management Co. in
Mumbai. “We have one of the fastest growth rates, plus we are
not dependent on the outside world as our domestic consumption
is very strong.”  The Bombay Stock Exchange’s Sensitive Index, or  Sensex ,
gained 95.45, or 0.5 percent, to 20,001.55. The gauge surpassed
20,000 for the first time since January 2008 and has climbed 25
percent from its May 25 low.  Foreign fund inflows to India’s equities have increased 54
percent this year, making the Sensex the most expensive
benchmark index in Asia and among the BRIC markets that also
comprise Brazil, Russia and China.  The S&P CNX  Nifty  Index on the National Stock Exchange
advanced 0.5 percent to 6,009.05. The  BSE 200 Index  rose 0.1
percent to 2,529.08.  Bharat Heavy  Bharat Heavy gained 1.5 percent to 2,479.35 rupees. Larsen
& Toubro increased 2 percent to 2,039.9 rupees, its highest
close since January 2008.  India’s gross domestic product expanded 8.8 percent last
quarter from a year earlier, the most among major economies
after China and Brazil.  The U.S. has fallen behind emerging markets in Brazil,
China and India as the preferred place to invest, a Bloomberg
survey shows, though the world’s largest economy still ranks
highest of all major developed countries.  In the September poll of 1,408 investors, analysts and
traders who are Bloomberg subscribers, respondents rate the U.S.
fourth for potential returns over the next year, behind Brazil
and China, tied for first, and India, in third place.  Best Performer  The Sensex has climbed 15 percent this year, making India
the best performer among the world’s 10 largest stock markets by
value. Its 14-day  relative strength index  is 82.9, the highest
since October 2007, according to data compiled by Bloomberg. The
reading suggests that India is the only market in Asia that is
“overbought,” according to Nomura Holdings Inc.  Investors should be “cautious for a pull-back,”  Kenneth Chan  and  Tacky Cheng , the Hong Kong-based analysts at Nomura
wrote in a report yesterday, citing “profit-taking concerns on
overbought and falling volume momentum breadth.”  ITC Ltd. , the biggest cigarette company, retreated 2.3
percent to 172.65 rupees. The stock yesterday reached its
highest level in at least 19 years and is the second-best
performer on the Sensex this year. Its 14-day relative strength
index crossed 70 yesterday, a level some investors see as a
signal to sell.  Fund Flows  Wockhardt Ltd.  soared 2 percent to 286.6 rupees after
Chairman  Habil Khorakiwala  yesterday said the drugmaker expects
sales to increase as much as 20 percent this year.  India’s gross domestic product expanded 8.8 percent last
quarter from a year earlier, the most among major economies
after China and Brazil.  Global  funds  bought a net  17.2 billion rupees  ($373.3
million) of Indian equities on Sept. 17, taking total
investments in the stocks this year to 735.4 billion rupees,
according to the nation’s market regulator.  Inflows from overseas reached a record 834.2 billion rupees
in 2009, exceeding the high set two years ago in local currency
terms, as the biggest advance in 18 years lured foreign funds.
They sold a record 529.9 billion rupees of shares in 2008,
triggering a record annual decline.  To contact the reporter on this story:
